{"title_page": "John Steenhuisen", "text_new": "{{short description|Interim  leader of the Democratic Alliance, Leader of the Opposition}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image              = John Steenhuisen DA MP.jpeg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Steenhuisen in 2011\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n| name               = John Steenhuisen\n| honorific-suffix   = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| office             = [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| president          = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| deputy             = \n| term_start         =  27 October 2019\n| term_end           = \n| predecessor        = [[Annelie Lotriet]] (acting)<br />[[Mmusi Maimane]]\n| successor          = \n| office1            =Leader of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] <br/> {{small|Interim}}\n|1blankname1         = {{nowrap|Chair}}\n|1namedata1          = [[Ivan Meyer]] (interim)\n| term_start1        = 17 November 2019\n| term_end1          = \n| predecessor1       = Mmusi Maimane\n| status1            = \n| successor1         = \n| office2            = [[National Assembly (South Africa)|Chief Whip of the Official Opposition]]\n| deputy2            = [[Jacques Julius]]<br />[[Mike Waters (politician)|Mike Waters]]\n| term_start2        =  29 May 2014\n| term_end2          = 24 October 2019\n| predecessor2       = [[Watty Watson]]\n| leader2            = Mmusi Maimane\n| successor2         = Jacques Julius (acting)<br>[[Natasha Mazzone]]\n| office3            = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]]\n| term_start3        = 19 July 2011\n| term_end3          =\n| predecessor3       = \n| constituency3      = \n| office4            = Member of the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature|KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Legislature]]\n| term_start4        = 22 April 2009\n| term_end4          = 19 July 2011\n| successor4         =\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (Until 2000)\n| alma_mater         = [[Northwood School (Durban North, South Africa)|Northwood Boys High School]]\n| birthname          = John Henry Steenhuisen\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|3|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province|Natal]], [[South Africa]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Terry Steenhuisen (n\u00e9e Kass Beaumont)|2014}}<br />{{marriage|Julie Steenhuisen (n\u00e9e Wright)<br />|2000|2010|end=divorced}}\n| children           = 3\n}}\n\n'''John Henry Steenhuisen''' (born 25 March 1976) is a [[South Africa]]n politician who has been serving as the [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]] in the [[National Assembly]] since October 2019 and the interim Federal Leader of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] since November 2019. He previously served as the Chief Whip of the Official Opposition under the leadership of [[Mmusi Maimane]] from May 2014 to October 2019. He has been serving as a Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] since July 2011. Prior to his appointment to the National Assembly, he was involved with the politics of KwaZulu-Natal, serving as the Provincial Leader of the DA and the party's caucus leader in the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.da.org.za/our_people.htm?action=view-page&category=members-of-provincial-legislatures&province=kwazulu-natal|title=DA Caucus KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Legislature: John Steenhuisen|publisher=Democratic Alliance|accessdate=26 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020112052/http://da.org.za/our_people.htm?action=view-page&category=members-of-provincial-legislatures&province=kwazulu-natal|archivedate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIdeologically, Steenhuisen describes himself as a [[liberalism|liberal]] and a supporter of [[non-racialism]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steenhuisen |first1=John |title=We can fix the DA - John Steenhuisen |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/we-can-fix-the-da--john-steenhuisen |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=16 February 2020 |quote=However, as a liberal, I am also against all forms of racial labelling, classification and categorisation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahlati |first1=Zintle |title=Race should not be a factor in whose elected DA leader, says Steenhuisen |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/race-should-not-be-a-factor-in-whose-elected-da-leader-says-steenhuisen-37071794 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=IOL news |date=12 November 2019 |location=Johannesburg |quote=Steenhuisen spoke candidly about his views on race and said what lost the DA votes at the general election was diverting from the party\u2019s principles and race.  'We should be a party that upholds its values of non-racialism and rejects representativity...'}}</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\n===Early life and education===\nSteenhuisen was born in [[Durban]] and attended [[Northwood School (Durban North, South Africa)|Northwood Boys High School]], an English-medium secondary school located in Durban, from 1989 until matric in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/john-steenhuisen-52aa968b/|title=John Steenhuisen LinkedIn Profile|publisher=[[LinkedIn]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Steenhuisen was criticised in media reports which revealed that he did not have a tertiary education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/news/twitter-has-field-day-over-das-steenhuisens-lack-qualifications|title=Twitter has field day over DA's Steenhuisen's lack of qualifications|publisher=[[eNCA]]|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nHe currently resides in [[Umhlanga, KwaZulu-Natal]] and is a supporter of the [[Sharks (rugby union)|Sharks]] rugby union team and [[AmaZulu F.C.]] football club.<ref name=\"cse\">{{cite web |title=JOHN STEENHUISEN |url=https://coresharesevents.co.za/speaker/john-steenhuisen/ |website=coresharesevents.co.za |accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen was married for 10 years to Julie Steenhuisen (n\u00e9e Wright), a fellow Durban native. They were divorced in October 2010, amid public revelations of his ongoing affair with Terry Kass Beaumont, the DA's provincial spokesperson and wife of Michael Beaumont, the DA's provincial director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Archives/City-Press/DA-leader-quits-over-sex-scandal-20150429|title=DA leader quits over sex scandal|publisher=[[News24]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> \nSteenhuisen has two daughters from his first marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/kwazulu-natal/mr-clean-under-fire-688325|title=Mr Clean under fire|publisher=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> He is now married to Terry Steenhuisen and they have a daughter together.<ref name=\"cse\" />\n\nSteenhuisen is fluent in both [[English language|English]] and [[Afrikaans]].<ref name=\"cse\" />\n\n==Political career==\n[[File: John Steenhuisen with Winston in 2011.jpg|250px|left|thumb|[[Winston Rabotapi]] and Steenhuisen in 2011]]\n\nSteenhuisen started as an ordinary [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (predecessor to the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]) activist before he became a branch member.<ref name=\"DL\">{{cite news |last1=Swana |first1=Annelisa |title=Steenhuisen has a plan as he guns for DA's top spot |url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/news/2019-11-16-steenhuisen-has-a-plan-as-he-guns-for-das-top-spot/ |accessdate=16 November 2019 |agency=DispatchLIVE |date=16 November 2019 |quote=He then became regional chair, a councillor, caucus leader, an MPL, a provincial leader, an MP, a whip, a chief whip and eventually parliamentary leader.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, at the age of 22, Steenhuisen was elected to the then Durban City Council and consequently became one of the youngest municipal councillors. He was appointed the caucus leader of the Democratic Alliance in 2006 and served on the city's Executive Committee.<ref name=\"cse\" /><ref name=\"DL\" />\n\nHe represented the constituency of [[Durban North]] in the eThekwini Municipal Council, and its precursor, the Durban City Council, for ten years until his election to the KwaZulu-Natal Legislature during the [[2009 South African general election]]. He was elected Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in [[KwaZulu-Natal]] at the party's 2009 Provincial Congress.<ref name=\"DL\" /> He held the position until he announced his resignation from the provincial leadership on 18 October 2010, amid the disclosure of marital unfaithfulness. Steenhuisen's resignation as provincial leader became effective on 24 October 2010, although he continued to serve as an MPL and DA caucus leader until his move to the National Assembly in July 2011.<ref name=\"DL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Changes-in-KZN-DA-leadership-20101019|title=Changes in KZN DA leadership|publisher=News24|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/the-mercury/20110705/281573762335620|title=DA caucus leader moves to Cape|publisher=[[The Mercury (South Africa)|The Mercury]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen joined the National Assembly in July 2011 by replacing [[Mark Steele (politician)|Mark Steele]], a Democratic Alliance MP who, in turn, assumed Steenhuisen's seat in the [[KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Legislature]].<ref name=\"DL\" /> Steenhuisen is a member of the Rules Committee. He previously served as a member of the Joint Standing Committee on the Financial Management of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gov.za/group-details/4229|title=Joint Standing Committee on the Financial Management of Parliament|publisher=Parliament of the Republic of South Africa|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> He also formerly served as the Democratic Alliance's Shadow Minister for [[Department of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs|Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DA: Statement by John Steenhuisen, Democratic Alliance shadow minister of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs, on bad municipal appointments (03/05/2012) |url=https://www.polity.org.za/article/da-statement-by-john-steenhuisen-democratic-alliance-shadow-minister-of-cooperative-governance-and-traditional-affairs-on-bad-municipal-appointments-2012-05-03 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=Polity |date=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen is known for his oratory skills and has delivered many speeches to Parliament that have been noted for their wit and incisive criticism of [[African National Congress]] leadership, including previous South African President [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/You/Archive/where-is-zuma-da-chief-whip-john-steenhuisen-doesnt-hold-back-in-parliament-speech-20170728|title='Where is Zuma?': DA chief whip John Steenhuisen doesn't hold back in Parliament speech|publisher=News24|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/prison-uniform-should-be-zumas-exit-package-steenhuisen-20170726|title='Prison uniform should be Zuma's exit package' - Steenhuisen|publisher=News24|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen was appointed Chief Whip of the DA caucus on 29 May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Maimane appointed DA Parly leader |url=https://ewn.co.za/2014/05/29/Maimane-elected-to-lead-DA-in-Parliament |agency=EWN |date=29 May 2014 |location=Cape Town}}</ref> He was reappointed to the post in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=DA elects new caucus leadership, Mike Waters won't return as deputy chief whip |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/da-elects-new-caucus-leadership-mike-waters-wont-return-as-deputy-chief-whip-20190530 |accessdate=13 November 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership of the Democratic Alliance (2019\u2013present)==\n===Interim leadership election===\n[[Mmusi Maimane]] resigned as Federal Leader and Parliamentary Leader of the Democratic Alliance in October 2019, causing Steenhuisen to lose the title of chief whip. Steenhuisen's deputy, Jacques Julius, served as the acting chief whip.<ref>{{cite news |title=In pictures: John Steenhuisen announces his resignation as chief whip of the DA |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-10-24-in-pictures-john-steenhuisen-announces-his-resignation-as-chief-whip-of-the-da |accessdate=24 October 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> Steenhuisen declared his candidacy to succeed Maimane as parliamentary leader and was elected unopposed on 27 October 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=DA 'backbencher' John Steenhuisen lobbied to lead |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/da-backbencher-john-steenhuisen-lobbied-to-lead-20191024 |accessdate=24 October 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Etheridge |first1=Jenna |title=John Steenhuisen chosen as DA parliamentary leader |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-john-steenhuisen-chosen-as-da-parliamentary-leader-20191027 |accessdate=27 October 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe formally announced on 28 October 2019 that he would run for Federal Leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steenhuisen wants to take DA to new heights |url=https://www.enca.com/news/steenhuisen-wants-take-da-new-heights |accessdate=29 October 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Knight |first1=Tessa |title=Remoulding the 'big blue jelly': John Steenhuisen to run for top DA post |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-10-28-remoulding-the-big-blue-jelly-john-steenhuisen-to-run-for-top-da-post/ |accessdate=29 October 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=28 October 2019}}</ref> He was elected to the position on an interim capacity on 17 November 2019 after he defeated Gauteng MPL [[Makashule Gana]].<ref>{{cite news |title=JUST IN l DA chooses Steenhuisen, Meyer as interim federal leader and chair |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-da-chooses-steenhuisen-meyer-as-interim-federal-leader-and-chair-20191117 |accessdate=17 November 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020 leadership campaign===\nOn 15 February 2020, he declared his intention to seek a full-term as Federal Leader of the Democratic Alliance at the Hellenic Community Centre in [[Mouille Point]], [[Cape Town]]. Several public representatives attended the launch of his campaign, including Western Cape Premier [[Alan Winde]], the head of the party's governance unit [[James Selfe]], Shadow Minister of Justice and Correctional Services [[Glynnis Breytenbach]], and DA chief whip in the National Assembly [[Natasha Mazzone]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=DA leadership race: Steenhuisen 'in it to win it' |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/da-leadership-race-steenhuisen-in-it-to-win-it-20200215 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Steenhuisen vows to unite DA |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/steenhuisen-vows-to-unite-da/ |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=SABC News |date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chothia |first1=Andrea |title=\u2018I want to free you from Eskom,\u2019 says John Steenhuisen |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/john-steenhuisen-da-federal-leader-campaign-2020/ |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=15 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nSteenhuisen is facing Gauteng provincial leader [[John Moodey]] and KwaZulu-Natal MPL [[Mbali Ntuli]] for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mailovich |first1=Claudi |title=DA leadership: Race to the finish |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/fm/fm-fox/2020-02-27-da-leadership-race-to-the-finish/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=Financial Mail |date=27 February 2020}}</ref> He is regarded as the frontrunner for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kiewit |first1=Lester |title=Steenhuisen takes the lead in DA race while Ntuli falters |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2020-02-19-steenhuisen-takes-the-lead-in-da-race-while-ntuli-falters/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=Mail & Guardian |date=19 February 2020|quote=The campaign for Democratic Alliance leader has seen interim leader John Steenhuisen come out as the clear frontrunner in the race to permanently replace Mmusi Maimane.}}</ref> He has the endorsements from seven out of the nine DA provincial leaders.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cele |first1=Sthembile |last2=Masuabi |first2=Queenin |title=John Steenhuisen scores major boost as provincial DA leaders throw weight behind him |url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/john-steenhuisen-scores-major-boost-as-provincial-da-leaders-throw-weight-behind-him-20200216 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=city-press.news24.com |date=16 February 2020}}</ref> KwaZulu-Natal provincial leader [[Zwakele Mncwango]] is backing Ntuli.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nkosikhona |first1=Duma |title=DA KZN leader Mcwango rallies behind Ntuli to become national party leader |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/03/da-kzn-leader-mcwango-rallies-behind-ntuli-to-become-national-party-leader |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper= Eyewitness News (EWN)|location=Durban |date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe party was scheduled [[2020 Democratic Alliance Federal Congress|to elect]] its new leadership in May, but this has been postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mavuso |first1=Sihle |title=ANC, DA postpone conferences amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/anc-da-postpone-conferences-amid-coronavirus-fears-44967442 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=IOL |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Steenhuisen has since temporarily suspended all campaign activities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Dan |title=Steenhuisen puts DA leadership charge on hold amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/steenhuisen-coronavirus-da-leadership-suspended-2020/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other activities===\nIn the early days of Steenhuisen's leadership, the party lost control of the [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality]] in December 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kobokana |first1=Abongwe |title=DA disappointed at losing Joburg Mayor vote |url=https://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/da-disappointed-at-losing-joburg-mayor-vote/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=SABC News |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> In August 2016, then-DA leader Mmusi Maimane formed an informal alliance with the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] to secure control of several hung municipalities, including Johannesburg with [[Herman Mashaba]] of the DA as the city's mayor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Manyathela |first1=Clement |last2=Kekana |first2=Masa |title=Victory for DA as Herman Mashaba is elected Mayor of Johannesburg |url=https://ewn.co.za/2016/08/22/Victory-for-DA-as-Herman-Mashaba-is-elected-Mayor-of-Johannesburg |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=22 August 2016}}</ref> Mashaba resigned as mayor in October 2019 and left office in November.<ref>{{cite news |title=Herman Mashaba: Johannesburg's black mayor resigns over DA race row |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-50123953 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=BBC News |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> A vacancy was therefore created. DA Gauteng leader [[John Moodey]] and party provincial chair [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]] were seen as being supportive of the EFF co-operation with the DA.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joubert |first1=Jan-Jan |title=A backstory of betrayal: How the ANC took Joburg from the DA |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/how-did-the-da-lose-johannesburg-2019/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> DA Federal Council chair [[Helen Zille]] and Steenhuisen both opposed a coalition agreement with the EFF.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joubert |first1=Jan-Jan |title=Helen Zille sets out DA\u2019s road to recovery \u2013 talks race, EFF and more |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/lifestyle/opinion/helen-zille-da-road-to-recovery-steenhuisen-challenge-november-2019/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |agency=The South African |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> On 4 December, the ANC regained control of the city of Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mailovich |first1=Claudi |title=ANC retakes Joburg as DA coalition collapses |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-12-04-anc-regains-control-of-city-of-johannesburg/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=BusinessLIVE |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Previous DA coalition partners and a few DA councillors voted for the ANC candidate [[Geoff Makhubo]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feketha |first1=Siviwe |title=DA feels 'betrayed' by councillors, coalition partners after ANC victory in Joburg |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/da-feels-betrayed-by-councillors-coalition-partners-after-anc-victory-in-joburg-38624535 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=IOL news |date=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Steenhuisen announced that he would be undertaking a \"Real State of the Nation Address Tour\" ahead of President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]'s address. The tour started on 27 January and ended two weeks later before the SONA on 13 February. He and DA leadership visited multiple provinces to highlight the service delivery issues and challenges that communities are met with.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kahla |first1=Cheryl |title=DA to embark on \u2018Real State of The Nation Tour\u2019, says Steenhuisen |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/da-john-steenhuisen-real-state-of-the-nation-tour-27-january-2020/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=The South Africa |date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhengu |first1=Cebelihle |title='The real state of the nation': Five takeouts from John Steenhuisen's tour |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2020-02-04-the-real-state-of-the-nation-five-takeouts-from-john-steenhuisens-tour/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{People's Assembly (South Africa) | john-henry-steenhuisen |John Steenhuisen}}\n* [https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/348 Mr John Henry Steenhuisen \u2013 Parliament of South Africa]\n* [https://www.da.org.za/people/john-steenhuisen John Steenhuisen Interim Federal Leader \u2013 Democratic Alliance]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mmusi Maimane]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Interim Leader of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mmusi Maimane]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]] in the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Watty Watson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chief Whip of the Official Opposition in the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]|years=2014\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jacques Julius]] (acting)<br/>[[Natasha Mazzone]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}}\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Liberalism in South Africa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steenhuisen, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Members of the KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Northwood School, Durban]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Interim  leader of the Democratic Alliance, Leader of the Opposition}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image              = John Steenhuisen DA MP.jpeg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Steenhuisen in 2011\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n| name               = John Steenhuisen\n| honorific-suffix   = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| office             = [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| president          = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| deputy             = \n| term_start         =  27 October 2019\n| term_end           = \n| predecessor        = [[Annelie Lotriet]] (acting)<br />[[Mmusi Maimane]]\n| successor          = \n| office1            =Leader of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] <br/> {{small|Interim}}\n|1blankname1         = {{nowrap|Chair}}\n|1namedata1          = [[Ivan Meyer]] (interim)\n| term_start1        = 17 November 2019\n| term_end1          = \n| predecessor1       = Mmusi Maimane\n| status1            = \n| successor1         = \n| office2            = [[National Assembly (South Africa)|Chief Whip of the Official Opposition]]\n| deputy2            = [[Jacques Julius]]<br />[[Mike Waters (politician)|Mike Waters]]\n| term_start2        =  29 May 2014\n| term_end2          = 24 October 2019\n| predecessor2       = [[Watty Watson]]\n| leader2            = Mmusi Maimane\n| successor2         = Jacques Julius (acting)<br>[[Natasha Mazzone]]\n| office3            = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]]\n| term_start3        = 19 July 2011\n| term_end3          =\n| predecessor3       = \n| constituency3      = \n| office4            = Member of the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature|KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Legislature]]\n| term_start4        = 22 April 2009\n| term_end4          = 19 July 2011\n| successor4         =\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (Until 2000)\n| alma_mater         = [[Northwood School (Durban North, South Africa)|Northwood Boys High School]]\n| birthname          = John Henry Steenhuisen\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|3|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province|Natal]], [[South Africa]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Terry Steenhuisen (n\u00e9e Kass Beaumont)|2014}}<br />{{marriage|Julie Steenhuisen (n\u00e9e Wright)<br />|2000|2010|end=divorced}}\n| children           = 3\n}}\n\n'''John Henry Steenhuisen''' (born 25 March 1976) is a [[South Africa]]n politician who has been serving as the [[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]] in the [[National Assembly]] since October 2019 and the interim Federal Leader of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] since November 2019. He previously served as the Chief Whip of the Official Opposition under the leadership of [[Mmusi Maimane]] from May 2014 to October 2019. He has been serving as a Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] since July 2011. Prior to his appointment to the National Assembly, he was involved with the politics of KwaZulu-Natal, serving as the Provincial Leader of the DA and the party's caucus leader in the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.da.org.za/our_people.htm?action=view-page&category=members-of-provincial-legislatures&province=kwazulu-natal|title=DA Caucus KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Legislature: John Steenhuisen|publisher=Democratic Alliance|accessdate=26 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020112052/http://da.org.za/our_people.htm?action=view-page&category=members-of-provincial-legislatures&province=kwazulu-natal|archivedate=20 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIdeologically, Steenhuisen describes himself as a [[liberalism|liberal]] and a supporter of [[non-racialism]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steenhuisen |first1=John |title=We can fix the DA - John Steenhuisen |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/we-can-fix-the-da--john-steenhuisen |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=16 February 2020 |quote=However, as a liberal, I am also against all forms of racial labelling, classification and categorisation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahlati |first1=Zintle |title=Race should not be a factor in whose elected DA leader, says Steenhuisen |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/race-should-not-be-a-factor-in-whose-elected-da-leader-says-steenhuisen-37071794 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=IOL news |date=12 November 2019 |location=Johannesburg |quote=Steenhuisen spoke candidly about his views on race and said what lost the DA votes at the general election was diverting from the party\u2019s principles and race.  'We should be a party that upholds its values of non-racialism and rejects representativity...'}}</ref>\n\n==Family and personal life==\n===Early life and education===\nSteenhuisen was born in [[Durban]] and attended [[Northwood School (Durban North, South Africa)|Northwood Boys High School]], an English-medium secondary school located in Durban, from 1989 until matric in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/john-steenhuisen-52aa968b/|title=John Steenhuisen LinkedIn Profile|publisher=[[LinkedIn]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Steenhuisen was criticised in media reports which revealed that he did not have a tertiary education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/news/twitter-has-field-day-over-das-steenhuisens-lack-qualifications|title=Twitter has field day over DA's Steenhuisen's lack of qualifications|publisher=[[eNCA]]|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nHe currently resides in [[Umhlanga, KwaZulu-Natal]] and is a supporter of the [[Sharks (rugby union)|Sharks]] rugby union team and [[AmaZulu F.C.]] football club.<ref name=\"cse\">{{cite web |title=JOHN STEENHUISEN |url=https://coresharesevents.co.za/speaker/john-steenhuisen/ |website=coresharesevents.co.za |accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen was married for 10 years to Julie Steenhuisen (n\u00e9e Wright), a fellow Durban native. They were divorced in October 2010, amid public revelations of his ongoing affair with Terry Kass Beaumont, the DA's provincial spokesperson and wife of Michael Beaumont, the DA's provincial director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Archives/City-Press/DA-leader-quits-over-sex-scandal-20150429|title=DA leader quits over sex scandal|publisher=[[News24]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> \nSteenhuisen has two daughters from his first marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/kwazulu-natal/mr-clean-under-fire-688325|title=Mr Clean under fire|publisher=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> He is now married to Terry Steenhuisen and they have a daughter together.<ref name=\"cse\" />\n\nSteenhuisen is fluent in both [[English language|English]] and [[Afrikaans]].<ref name=\"cse\" />\n\n==Political career==\n[[File: John Steenhuisen with Winston in 2011.jpg|250px|left|thumb|[[Winston Rabotapi]] and Steenhuisen in 2011]]\n\nSteenhuisen started as an ordinary [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (predecessor to the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]) activist before he became a branch member.<ref name=\"DL\">{{cite news |last1=Swana |first1=Annelisa |title=Steenhuisen has a plan as he guns for DA's top spot |url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/news/2019-11-16-steenhuisen-has-a-plan-as-he-guns-for-das-top-spot/ |accessdate=16 November 2019 |agency=DispatchLIVE |date=16 November 2019 |quote=He then became regional chair, a councillor, caucus leader, an MPL, a provincial leader, an MP, a whip, a chief whip and eventually parliamentary leader.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, at the age of 22, Steenhuisen was elected to the then Durban City Council and consequently became one of the youngest municipal councillors. He was appointed the caucus leader of the Democratic Alliance in 2006 and served on the city's Executive Committee.<ref name=\"cse\" /><ref name=\"DL\" />\n\nHe represented the constituency of [[Durban North]] in the eThekwini Municipal Council, and its precursor, the Durban City Council, for ten years until his election to the KwaZulu-Natal Legislature during the [[2009 South African general election]]. He was elected Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in [[KwaZulu-Natal]] at the party's 2009 Provincial Congress.<ref name=\"DL\" /> He held the position until he announced his resignation from the provincial leadership on 18 October 2010, amid the disclosure of marital unfaithfulness. Steenhuisen's resignation as provincial leader became effective on 24 October 2010, although he continued to serve as an MPL and DA caucus leader until his move to the National Assembly in July 2011.<ref name=\"DL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Changes-in-KZN-DA-leadership-20101019|title=Changes in KZN DA leadership|publisher=News24|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/the-mercury/20110705/281573762335620|title=DA caucus leader moves to Cape|publisher=[[The Mercury (South Africa)|The Mercury]]|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen joined the National Assembly in July 2011 by replacing [[Mark Steele (politician)|Mark Steele]], a Democratic Alliance MP who, in turn, assumed Steenhuisen's seat in the [[KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Legislature]].<ref name=\"DL\" /> Steenhuisen is a member of the Rules Committee. He previously served as a member of the Joint Standing Committee on the Financial Management of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gov.za/group-details/4229|title=Joint Standing Committee on the Financial Management of Parliament|publisher=Parliament of the Republic of South Africa|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> He also formerly served as the Democratic Alliance's Shadow Minister for [[Department of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs|Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DA: Statement by John Steenhuisen, Democratic Alliance shadow minister of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs, on bad municipal appointments (03/05/2012) |url=https://www.polity.org.za/article/da-statement-by-john-steenhuisen-democratic-alliance-shadow-minister-of-cooperative-governance-and-traditional-affairs-on-bad-municipal-appointments-2012-05-03 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=Polity |date=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen is known for his oratory skills and has delivered many speeches to Parliament that have been noted for their wit and incisive criticism of [[African National Congress]] leadership, including previous South African President [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/You/Archive/where-is-zuma-da-chief-whip-john-steenhuisen-doesnt-hold-back-in-parliament-speech-20170728|title='Where is Zuma?': DA chief whip John Steenhuisen doesn't hold back in Parliament speech|publisher=News24|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/prison-uniform-should-be-zumas-exit-package-steenhuisen-20170726|title='Prison uniform should be Zuma's exit package' - Steenhuisen|publisher=News24|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteenhuisen was appointed Chief Whip of the DA caucus on 29 May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Maimane appointed DA Parly leader |url=https://ewn.co.za/2014/05/29/Maimane-elected-to-lead-DA-in-Parliament |agency=EWN |date=29 May 2014 |location=Cape Town}}</ref> He was reappointed to the post in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=DA elects new caucus leadership, Mike Waters won't return as deputy chief whip |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/da-elects-new-caucus-leadership-mike-waters-wont-return-as-deputy-chief-whip-20190530 |accessdate=13 November 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership of the Democratic Alliance (2019\u2013present)==\n===Interim leadership election===\n[[Mmusi Maimane]] resigned as Federal Leader and Parliamentary Leader of the Democratic Alliance in October 2019, causing Steenhuisen to lose the title of chief whip. Steenhuisen's deputy, Jacques Julius, served as the acting chief whip.<ref>{{cite news |title=In pictures: John Steenhuisen announces his resignation as chief whip of the DA |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-10-24-in-pictures-john-steenhuisen-announces-his-resignation-as-chief-whip-of-the-da |accessdate=24 October 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> Steenhuisen declared his candidacy to succeed Maimane as parliamentary leader and was elected unopposed on 27 October 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=DA 'backbencher' John Steenhuisen lobbied to lead |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/da-backbencher-john-steenhuisen-lobbied-to-lead-20191024 |accessdate=24 October 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Etheridge |first1=Jenna |title=John Steenhuisen chosen as DA parliamentary leader |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-john-steenhuisen-chosen-as-da-parliamentary-leader-20191027 |accessdate=27 October 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe formally announced on 28 October 2019 that he would run for Federal Leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steenhuisen wants to take DA to new heights |url=https://www.enca.com/news/steenhuisen-wants-take-da-new-heights |accessdate=29 October 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Knight |first1=Tessa |title=Remoulding the 'big blue jelly': John Steenhuisen to run for top DA post |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-10-28-remoulding-the-big-blue-jelly-john-steenhuisen-to-run-for-top-da-post/ |accessdate=29 October 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=28 October 2019}}</ref> He was elected to the position on an interim capacity on 17 November 2019 after he defeated Gauteng MPL [[Makashule Gana]].<ref>{{cite news |title=JUST IN l DA chooses Steenhuisen, Meyer as interim federal leader and chair |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-da-chooses-steenhuisen-meyer-as-interim-federal-leader-and-chair-20191117 |accessdate=17 November 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020 leadership campaign===\nOn 15 February 2020, he declared his intention to seek a full-term as Federal Leader of the Democratic Alliance at the Hellenic Community Centre in [[Mouille Point]], [[Cape Town]]. Several public representatives attended the launch of his campaign, including Western Cape Premier [[Alan Winde]], the head of the party's governance unit [[James Selfe]], Shadow Minister of Justice and Correctional Services [[Glynnis Breytenbach]], and DA chief whip in the National Assembly [[Natasha Mazzone]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gerber |first1=Jan |title=DA leadership race: Steenhuisen 'in it to win it' |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/da-leadership-race-steenhuisen-in-it-to-win-it-20200215 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Steenhuisen vows to unite DA |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/steenhuisen-vows-to-unite-da/ |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=SABC News |date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chothia |first1=Andrea |title=\u2018I want to free you from Eskom,\u2019 says John Steenhuisen |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/john-steenhuisen-da-federal-leader-campaign-2020/ |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=15 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nSteenhuisen is facing Gauteng provincial leader [[John Moodey]] and KwaZulu-Natal MPL [[Mbali Ntuli]] for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mailovich |first1=Claudi |title=DA leadership: Race to the finish |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/fm/fm-fox/2020-02-27-da-leadership-race-to-the-finish/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=Financial Mail |date=27 February 2020}}</ref> He is regarded as the frontrunner for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kiewit |first1=Lester |title=Steenhuisen takes the lead in DA race while Ntuli falters |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2020-02-19-steenhuisen-takes-the-lead-in-da-race-while-ntuli-falters/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=Mail & Guardian |date=19 February 2020|quote=The campaign for Democratic Alliance leader has seen interim leader John Steenhuisen come out as the clear frontrunner in the race to permanently replace Mmusi Maimane.}}</ref> He has the endorsements from seven out of the nine DA provincial leaders.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cele |first1=Sthembile |last2=Masuabi |first2=Queenin |title=John Steenhuisen scores major boost as provincial DA leaders throw weight behind him |url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/john-steenhuisen-scores-major-boost-as-provincial-da-leaders-throw-weight-behind-him-20200216 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=city-press.news24.com |date=16 February 2020}}</ref> KwaZulu-Natal provincial leader [[Zwakele Mncwango]] is backing Ntuli.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nkosikhona |first1=Duma |title=DA KZN leader Mcwango rallies behind Ntuli to become national party leader |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/03/da-kzn-leader-mcwango-rallies-behind-ntuli-to-become-national-party-leader |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper= Eyewitness News (EWN)|location=Durban |date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe party was scheduled [[2020 Democratic Alliance Federal Congress|to elect]] its new leadership in May, but this has been postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mavuso |first1=Sihle |title=ANC, DA postpone conferences amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/anc-da-postpone-conferences-amid-coronavirus-fears-44967442 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=IOL |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Steenhuisen has since temporarily suspended all campaign activities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Dan |title=Steenhuisen puts DA leadership charge on hold amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/steenhuisen-coronavirus-da-leadership-suspended-2020/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other activities===\nIn the early days of Steenhuisen's leadership, the party lost control of the [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality]] in December 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kobokana |first1=Abongwe |title=DA disappointed at losing Joburg Mayor vote |url=https://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/da-disappointed-at-losing-joburg-mayor-vote/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=SABC News |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> In August 2016, then-DA leader Mmusi Maimane formed an informal alliance with the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] to secure control of several hung municipalities, including Johannesburg with [[Herman Mashaba]] of the DA as the city's mayor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Manyathela |first1=Clement |last2=Kekana |first2=Masa |title=Victory for DA as Herman Mashaba is elected Mayor of Johannesburg |url=https://ewn.co.za/2016/08/22/Victory-for-DA-as-Herman-Mashaba-is-elected-Mayor-of-Johannesburg |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=22 August 2016}}</ref> Mashaba resigned as mayor in October 2019 and left office in November.<ref>{{cite news |title=Herman Mashaba: Johannesburg's black mayor resigns over DA race row |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-50123953 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=BBC News |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> A vacancy was therefore created. DA Gauteng leader [[John Moodey]] and party provincial chair [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]] were seen as being supportive of the EFF co-operation with the DA.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joubert |first1=Jan-Jan |title=A backstory of betrayal: How the ANC took Joburg from the DA |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/how-did-the-da-lose-johannesburg-2019/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=5 December 2019}}</ref> DA Federal Council chair [[Helen Zille]] and Steenhuisen both opposed a coalition agreement with the EFF.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joubert |first1=Jan-Jan |title=Helen Zille sets out DA\u2019s road to recovery \u2013 talks race, EFF and more |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/lifestyle/opinion/helen-zille-da-road-to-recovery-steenhuisen-challenge-november-2019/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |agency=The South African |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> On 4 December, the ANC regained control of the city of Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mailovich |first1=Claudi |title=ANC retakes Joburg as DA coalition collapses |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-12-04-anc-regains-control-of-city-of-johannesburg/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=BusinessLIVE |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Previous DA coalition partners and a few DA councillors voted for the ANC candidate [[Geoff Makhubo]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feketha |first1=Siviwe |title=DA feels 'betrayed' by councillors, coalition partners after ANC victory in Joburg |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/da-feels-betrayed-by-councillors-coalition-partners-after-anc-victory-in-joburg-38624535 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |newspaper=IOL news |date=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Steenhuisen announced that he would be undertaking a \"Real State of the Nation Address Tour\" ahead of President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]'s address. The tour started on 27 January and ended two weeks later before the SONA on 13 February. He and DA leadership visited multiple provinces to highlight the service delivery issues and challenges that communities are met with.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kahla |first1=Cheryl |title=DA to embark on \u2018Real State of The Nation Tour\u2019, says Steenhuisen |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/da-john-steenhuisen-real-state-of-the-nation-tour-27-january-2020/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=The South Africa |date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhengu |first1=Cebelihle |title='The real state of the nation': Five takeouts from John Steenhuisen's tour |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2020-02-04-the-real-state-of-the-nation-five-takeouts-from-john-steenhuisens-tour/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{People's Assembly (South Africa) | john-henry-steenhuisen |John Steenhuisen }}\n* [https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/348 Mr John Henry Steenhuisen \u2013 Parliament of South Africa]\n* [https://www.da.org.za/people/john-steenhuisen John Steenhuisen Interim Federal Leader \u2013 Democratic Alliance]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mmusi Maimane]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Interim Leader of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mmusi Maimane]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (South Africa)|Leader of the Opposition]] in the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Watty Watson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chief Whip of the Official Opposition in the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]|years=2014\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jacques Julius]] (acting)<br/>[[Natasha Mazzone]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}}\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Liberalism in South Africa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steenhuisen, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Members of the KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Northwood School, Durban]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n", "name_user": "Axxter99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Steenhuisen"}
{"title_page": "Oyster Bay Branch", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Long Island Rail Road branch}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Oyster Bay Branch\n|color       = {{LIRR color|Oyster Bay}}\n|image       = LIRR C3 5019 on Train 6506.jpg\n|image_width = 300px\n|caption     = [[Bilevel rail car|Double-decker]] Train #6506 to Oyster Bay at Mineola\n|type        = [[Commuter rail]]\n|system      = [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|USA]]\n|start       = Mineola\n|end         = Oyster Bay\n|stations    = 10\n|routes      = {{rail color box|system=LIRR|line=Oyster Bay}}\n|daily_ridership   = 6,000<ref name=\"2004 elim\">{{cite news | title = M.T.A.'s Threat Drops Some Jaws | first = Stewart | last = Ain | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/08/nyregion/mta-s-threat-drops-some-jaws.html | newspaper = The New York Times | date = August 8, 2004| accessdate = July 12, 2009}}</ref>\n|open        = 1865-1889\n|close       = \n|owner       = [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n|operator = [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]\n|linelength  = \n|tracklength = {{convert|14.68|mi|km|1}}\n|gauge       = {{RailGauge|ussg}}\n|electrification          = 750 [[volt|V]] ([[Direct current|DC]]) [[third rail]] south of [[East Williston (LIRR station)|East Williston]]\n|map         = {{Oyster Bay Branch}}\n}}\nThe '''Oyster Bay Branch''' is a [[rail line]] and service owned and operated by the [[Long Island Rail Road]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]]. The branch splits from the [[Main Line (Long Island Rail Road)|Main Line]] just east of [[Mineola (LIRR station)|Mineola]] station, and runs north and east to [[Oyster Bay (LIRR station)|Oyster Bay]].<ref>[http://mta.info/lirr/Timetable/lirrmap.htm LIRR map] ''MTA'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref> The branch is electrified between East Williston and Mineola.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Locust Valley Station.jpg|thumb|left|[[Locust Valley (LIRR station)|Locust Valley]], the line's eastern terminus in 1869]]\n\nThe first phase of what is now known as the Oyster Bay Branch opened on January 23, 1865. The line was built by the Glen Cove Branch Rail Road, a subsidiary of the Long Island Rail Road, and extended to [[Glen Head (LIRR station)|Glen Head]].<ref name=\"PRR 1865\">[http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR1865%20June%2004.wd.pdf PRR chronology: 1865] ''Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref> On May 16, 1867 the railway was extended to [[Glen Street (LIRR station)|Glen Cove]] (now known as Glen Street).<ref name=\"PRR 1867\">[http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR1867%20June%2004.wd.pdf PRR chronology: 1867] ''Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref> and on April 19, 1869 the line was extended further to [[Locust Valley (LIRR station)|Locust Valley]].<ref name=\"PRR 1869\">[http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR1869%20June%2004.wd.pdf PRR chronology: 1869] ''Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=68FHDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=oyster+bay+branch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig5v6KzvHaAhUsh-AKHYEwCwkQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=oyster%20bay%20branch&f=false|title=Long Island Rail Road: Oyster Bay Branch|last=Morrison|first=David D.|date=March 5, 2018|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=|isbn=9781467128544|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|8}}\n\nBy the early 1880s, there had been pressure to expand rail service eastward.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\">{{cite web | title=Oyster Bay, Mill Neck, and Syosset: The History of Long Island Rail Road Service to Northeastern Nassau County | website=Derek Stadler | date=September 21, 2014 | url=https://derekstadler.wordpress.com/portfolio-2/collections-photography/nassau/oyster-bay-mill-neck-and-syosset-the-history-of-long-island-rail-road-service-to-northeastern-nassau-county/ | accessdate=November 1, 2015}}</ref> At this time another railroad, the Northern Railroad of Long Island threatened the Long island Rail Road's monopoly.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The Northern Railroad was incorporated on March 23, 1881, and it planned to build a road from Astoria to Northport via Flushing, Great Neck, Glen Cove, Oyster Bay and Huntington.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> By June 1881, construction plans were authorized and in mid-July the building contract was signed, with work set to begin in August.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The Long Island Rail Road attempted to undermine the Northern Railroad's project before it could sell stock and acquire a roadbed.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> It was going to link its north side branches together as a continuous railroad to Northport.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Construction cost from Great Neck to Roslyn and from Locust Valley to Northport was approximately $400,000.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" />\n\nIn February 1883, Austin Corbin, president of the Long Island Rail Road, offered to supply iron and rolling stock for the extension to Oyster Bay if local residents provided the right-of-way.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" />  While citizens considered the offer, the Northern Railroad folded since not enough money was raised.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> With the threat eliminated, the extension of rail service to Oyster Bay was temporarily delayed.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The project was revived in 1886 when some citizens offered to secure a right-of-way.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> In June 1886, a public meeting was held and a committee of 15 was appointed to secure land.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Although officials were still contemplating a through line to Northport, the LIRR organized the Oyster Bay Extension Railroad on August 31, 1886, which authorized a five-mile road from Locust Valley to Oyster Bay.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Ground was broken for the project on August 15, 1887.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> One phase of construction was the building of a bridge over what is now Tunnel Street in Locust Valley.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The masonry project began in October 1888 and the arch was finished on April 13, 1889.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The entire bridge was completed by September.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" />\n\nOn June 24, 1889, the extension opened with a huge celebration in Oyster Bay.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> A ceremonial train of ten cars left Long Island City about 9:30&nbsp;a.m. and was met at Locust Valley by ten young ladies who decorated the locomotive with flags and wreaths.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Upon arrival at Oyster Bay, an organized procession commenced, which was viewed by 5,000 residents and visitors.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> On Tuesday, June 25, the extension opened for regular passenger service with eight round trips daily to and from Long Island City.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /><ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|8}}\n\nThe line ended at Locust Valley for two decades until a final extension added four miles to [[Oyster Bay (LIRR station)|Oyster Bay]]. One of the reasons for building to Oyster Bay was to create a connection to New England. A large pier, now owned by the Flowers Oyster Company, was built to facilitate the loading of passenger cars onto a ferry, specifically to the [[Danbury and Norwalk Railroad]] station and ferry pier in [[Norwalk, Connecticut#Neighborhoods|Wilson's Point]] section of [[Norwalk, Connecticut]]. Service lasted only a few years as overland service from New York to Boston, once thought impossible, commenced.\n\nIn early 1892, a second track was built between Mineola and Albertson.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://derekstadler.wordpress.com/portfolio-2/collections-photography/nassau/underutilized-tracks-a-chronicle-of-electric-train-service-to-east-williston-and-a-history-of-the-neighboring-communities/|title=Underutilized Tracks: A Chronicle of Electric Train Service to East Williston and a History of the Neighboring Communities|last=Stadler|first=Derek|date=November 15, 2014|website=Derek Stadler|access-date=May 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===20th century to present===\nThe line was double-tracked to Roslyn, Glen Cove and Locust Valley in 1905, 1909 and 1911, respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112089483272;view=1up;seq=80|title=The Long Island Railroad Twenty-Seventh Annual Report For The Year Ending December 31st, 1908|last=|first=|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=1909|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|19}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ijgwAQAAMAAJ&dq=oyster+bay+branch+second+track+1911&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=locust+valley|title=Annual Report of the Long Island Rail Road Company to the Interstate Commerce Commission for the Year Ended December 31, 1911|last=|first=|date=1912|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 24, 1911|title=New Incorporations, Surveys, Etc.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SwQjAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA368&dq=glen+cove+chamber+of+commerce+oyster+bay+branch+electrification&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ2bO31fHaAhUCMt8KHXoGC78Q6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=glen%20cove%20chamber%20of%20commerce%20oyster%20bay%20branch%20electrification&f=false|journal=Railway Age|volume=50|issue=8|pages=368|via=}}</ref> The extension of the line's second track was done in anticipation of electrification.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112089483272;view=1up;seq=80|title=The Long Island Railroad Twenty-Eighth Annual Report For The Year Ending December 31st, 1909|last=|first=|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|21}}\n\nUntil 1928, a direct connection to the [[West Hempstead Branch]] existed just east of Mineola station. This spur crossed the [[Main Line (Long Island Rail Road)|Main Line]], then terminated at the end of a wye at what was often called the Garden City Branch. Until passenger service was abandoned along this branch, passengers would transfer between the two lines at Mineola Station itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lirrhistory.com/minwhemp.html|title=Mineola to West Hempstead|work=lirrhistory.com}}</ref><ref>[http://trainsarefun.com/lirr/mineola/mineola.htm Mineola Station History (Steve Lynch's LIRR Maps, Photos, Charts, etc.)] (TrainsAreFun.com)</ref> \n\nIn November 1928, LIRR officials surveyed the branch to evaluate the feasibility of electrifying the line. The Glen Cove Chamber of Commerce petitioned the LIRR, advocating for electrification. In response, the Vice President of the LIRR, in December, stated that the LIRR had to deal with the completion of multiple grade crossing elimination projects before electrifying the Oyster Bay Branch, which was estimated to cost $3.28 million.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 15, 1928|title=Position of L.I. On Oyster Bay Electrification|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lZYlAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1203&dq=oyster+bay+branch+electrification&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlsLL0PHaAhWhxFkKHa7SAs0Q6AEIPDAD#v=onepage&q=oyster%20bay%20branch%20electrification&f=false|journal=Railway Age|publisher=Simmons\u2013Boardman Publishing Company|volume=85|issue=24|pages=1203|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBy June 1934, the section of the line between [[East Williston (LIRR station)|East Williston]] and [[Mineola (LIRR station)|Mineola]] was electrified, with the remainder of the branch expected to be electrified soon after.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|40}} However, the remainder of the work was not completed. Instead, the branch is served by diesel powered-locomotive trains (except for one AM peak train that originates at East Williston and ends at [[Pennsylvania Station (New York)|Penn Station]] using Electric-Multiple Units).<ref name=\"LIRR Stations\">{{cite book |last=Morrison |first=David D. |last2=Pakaluk |first2=Valerie |title=Long Island Rail Road Stations |year=2003 |publisher=Arcadia |location=Chicago |isbn=0-7385-1180-3 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=20BUDIVc-5AC&pg=PA57 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the LIRR replaced the bridge over West Shore Road between Locust Valley and Oyster Bay Stations.<ref>[http://web.mta.info/lirr/News/2009/OysterBay11-2009a.htm Vans Replace Oyster Bay Trains Weekend of November 21-22 (MTA-LIRR News; November 2009)]</ref>\n\n==Stations==\nWest of {{lirrs|Mineola}}, most trips go on to terminate at {{lirrs|Jamaica}}, with some rush hour trips ending at {{lirrs|Hunterspoint Avenue}} or {{lirrs|Penn Station}}.<ref name=timetable>[http://mta.info/lirr/Timetable/Branch/OysterBayBranch.pdf LIRR Oyster Bay Branch Timetable]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Zone\n!Location\n!Station\n![[Railway milepost|Miles (km)]]<br>from [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|NYP]]<ref>Station pages linked from [http://lirr42.mta.info/stations LIRR Stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907052709/http://lirr42.mta.info/stations |date=September 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n!Date<br>opened\n!Date<br>closed\n!Connections and notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|4\n|[[Mineola, New York|Mineola]]\n|{{lirrs|Mineola}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|20.3 (32.3)\n|1837\n|\n|[[Long Island Rail Road]]: [[Montauk Branch|Montauk]], [[Port Jefferson Branch|Port Jefferson]], [[Ronkonkoma Branch|Ronkonkoma]] branches<br>[[Nassau Inter-County Express]]: {{LI bus link|n22|n22X|N23|n24|n40|n41}}<br>Originally named Hempstead, then Branch or Hempstead Branch\n|-\n|[[East Williston, New York|East Williston]]\n|{{lirrs|East Williston}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|21.6 (34.8)\n|1880<ref name=\"East Williston\">{{cite book |last=Morrison |first=David D. |last2=Pakaluk |first2=Valerie |title=Long Island Rail Road Stations |year=2003 |publisher=Arcadia |location=Chicago |isbn=0-7385-1180-3 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=20BUDIVc-5AC&pg=PA57 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}<br>Terminus of [[railway electrification system|electrification]]\n|-\n|rowspan=11|7\n|[[Albertson, New York|Albertson]]\n|{{lirrs|Albertson}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|22.6 (36.4)\n|1875\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}\n|-\n|[[Roslyn, New York|Roslyn]]\n|{{lirrs|Roslyn}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|24.0 (38.6)\n|January 23, 1865\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n23|n27}}\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n|[[Wheatley Hills, New York|Wheatley Hills]]\n|{{lirrs|North Roslyn}}\n|\n|\n|1924\n|Originally named Wheatley Hills\n|-\n|[[Greenvale, New York|Greenvale]]\n|{{lirrs|Greenvale}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|26.0 (41.8)\n|1866\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}<br>Originally named Week's\n|-\n|[[Glen Head, New York|Glen Head]]\n|{{lirrs|Glen Head}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|27.2 (43.8)\n|January 23, 1865\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Glen Cove, New York|Glen Cove]]\n|{{lirrs|Sea Cliff}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|28.5 (45.9)\n|May 16, 1867\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}\n|-\n|{{lirrs|Glen Street}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|29.1 (45.2)\n|May 16, 1867\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n21|n27}}\n|-\n|{{lirrs|Glen Cove}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|29.7 (47.8)\n|1895\n|\n|Originally named Nassau\n|-\n|[[Locust Valley, New York|Locust Valley]]\n|{{lirrs|Locust Valley}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|30.8 (49.6)\n|April 19, 1869\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n|[[Mill Neck, New York|Mill Neck]]\n|{{lirrs|Mill Neck}}\n|\n|June 25, 1889\n|1998\n|Originally named Bayville\n|-\n|[[Oyster Bay, New York|Oyster Bay]]\n|{{lirrs|Oyster Bay}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|34.7 (55.8)\n|June 25, 1889\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons and category|Oyster Bay Branch|Oyster Bay Branch (Long Island Rail Road)}}\n* [http://www.lirrhistory.com/obsta.html Oyster Bay Branch Stations (Unofficial LIRR History web site)]\n* [http://world.nycsubway.org/us/lirr/lirr-oysterbay.html NYCSubways.org: Oyster Bay Branch]\n* [http://thelirrtoday.blogspot.com/search/label/Oyster%20Bay%20Branch Oyster Bay Branch (The LIRR Today)]\n\n{{Long Island Rail Road}}\n\n[[Category:Long Island Rail Road branches]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Nassau County, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Oyster Bay Branch\n|color       = {{LIRR color|Oyster Bay}}\n|image       = LIRR C3 5019 on Train 6506.jpg\n|image_width = 300px\n|caption     = [[Bilevel rail car|Double-decker]] Train #6506 to Oyster Bay at Mineola\n|type        = [[Commuter rail]]\n|system      = [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|USA]]\n|start       = Mineola\n|end         = Oyster Bay\n|stations    = 10\n|routes      = {{rail color box|system=LIRR|line=Oyster Bay}}\n|daily_ridership   = 6,000<ref name=\"2004 elim\">{{cite news | title = M.T.A.'s Threat Drops Some Jaws | first = Stewart | last = Ain | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/08/nyregion/mta-s-threat-drops-some-jaws.html | newspaper = The New York Times | date = August 8, 2004| accessdate = July 12, 2009}}</ref>\n|open        = 1865-1889\n|close       = \n|owner       = [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n|operator = [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]\n|linelength  = \n|tracklength = {{convert|14.68|mi|km|1}}\n|gauge       = {{RailGauge|ussg}}\n|electrification          = 750 [[volt|V]] ([[Direct current|DC]]) [[third rail]] south of [[East Williston (LIRR station)|East Williston]]\n|map         = {{Oyster Bay Branch}}\n}}\nThe '''Oyster Bay Branch''' is a [[rail line]] and service owned and operated by the [[Long Island Rail Road]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]]. The branch splits from the [[Main Line (Long Island Rail Road)|Main Line]] just east of [[Mineola (LIRR station)|Mineola]] station, and runs north and east to [[Oyster Bay (LIRR station)|Oyster Bay]].<ref>[http://mta.info/lirr/Timetable/lirrmap.htm LIRR map] ''MTA'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref> The branch is electrified between East Williston and Mineola.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Locust Valley Station.jpg|thumb|left|[[Locust Valley (LIRR station)|Locust Valley]], the line's eastern terminus in 1869]]\n\nThe first phase of what is now known as the Oyster Bay Branch opened on January 23, 1865. The line was built by the Glen Cove Branch Rail Road, a subsidiary of the Long Island Rail Road, and extended to [[Glen Head (LIRR station)|Glen Head]].<ref name=\"PRR 1865\">[http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR1865%20June%2004.wd.pdf PRR chronology: 1865] ''Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref> On May 16, 1867 the railway was extended to [[Glen Street (LIRR station)|Glen Cove]] (now known as Glen Street).<ref name=\"PRR 1867\">[http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR1867%20June%2004.wd.pdf PRR chronology: 1867] ''Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref> and on April 19, 1869 the line was extended further to [[Locust Valley (LIRR station)|Locust Valley]].<ref name=\"PRR 1869\">[http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR1869%20June%2004.wd.pdf PRR chronology: 1869] ''Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society'' Retrieved July 12, 2009</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=68FHDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=oyster+bay+branch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig5v6KzvHaAhUsh-AKHYEwCwkQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=oyster%20bay%20branch&f=false|title=Long Island Rail Road: Oyster Bay Branch|last=Morrison|first=David D.|date=March 5, 2018|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=|isbn=9781467128544|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|8}}\n\nBy the early 1880s, there had been pressure to expand rail service eastward.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\">{{cite web | title=Oyster Bay, Mill Neck, and Syosset: The History of Long Island Rail Road Service to Northeastern Nassau County | website=Derek Stadler | date=September 21, 2014 | url=https://derekstadler.wordpress.com/portfolio-2/collections-photography/nassau/oyster-bay-mill-neck-and-syosset-the-history-of-long-island-rail-road-service-to-northeastern-nassau-county/ | accessdate=November 1, 2015}}</ref> At this time another railroad, the Northern Railroad of Long Island threatened the Long island Rail Road's monopoly.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The Northern Railroad was incorporated on March 23, 1881, and it planned to build a road from Astoria to Northport via Flushing, Great Neck, Glen Cove, Oyster Bay and Huntington.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> By June 1881, construction plans were authorized and in mid-July the building contract was signed, with work set to begin in August.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The Long Island Rail Road attempted to undermine the Northern Railroad's project before it could sell stock and acquire a roadbed.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> It was going to link its north side branches together as a continuous railroad to Northport.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Construction cost from Great Neck to Roslyn and from Locust Valley to Northport was approximately $400,000.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" />\n\nIn February 1883, Austin Corbin, president of the Long Island Rail Road, offered to supply iron and rolling stock for the extension to Oyster Bay if local residents provided the right-of-way.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" />  While citizens considered the offer, the Northern Railroad folded since not enough money was raised.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> With the threat eliminated, the extension of rail service to Oyster Bay was temporarily delayed.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The project was revived in 1886 when some citizens offered to secure a right-of-way.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> In June 1886, a public meeting was held and a committee of 15 was appointed to secure land.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Although officials were still contemplating a through line to Northport, the LIRR organized the Oyster Bay Extension Railroad on August 31, 1886, which authorized a five-mile road from Locust Valley to Oyster Bay.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Ground was broken for the project on August 15, 1887.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> One phase of construction was the building of a bridge over what is now Tunnel Street in Locust Valley.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The masonry project began in October 1888 and the arch was finished on April 13, 1889.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> The entire bridge was completed by September.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" />\n\nOn June 24, 1889, the extension opened with a huge celebration in Oyster Bay.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> A ceremonial train of ten cars left Long Island City about 9:30&nbsp;a.m. and was met at Locust Valley by ten young ladies who decorated the locomotive with flags and wreaths.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> Upon arrival at Oyster Bay, an organized procession commenced, which was viewed by 5,000 residents and visitors.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /> On Tuesday, June 25, the extension opened for regular passenger service with eight round trips daily to and from Long Island City.<ref name=\"Derek Stadler 2014\" /><ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|8}}\n\nThe line ended at Locust Valley for two decades until a final extension added four miles to [[Oyster Bay (LIRR station)|Oyster Bay]]. One of the reasons for building to Oyster Bay was to create a connection to New England. A large pier, now owned by the Flowers Oyster Company, was built to facilitate the loading of passenger cars onto a ferry, specifically to the [[Danbury and Norwalk Railroad]] station and ferry pier in [[Norwalk, Connecticut#Neighborhoods|Wilson's Point]] section of [[Norwalk, Connecticut]]. Service lasted only a few years as overland service from New York to Boston, once thought impossible, commenced.\n\nIn early 1892, a second track was built between Mineola and Albertson.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://derekstadler.wordpress.com/portfolio-2/collections-photography/nassau/underutilized-tracks-a-chronicle-of-electric-train-service-to-east-williston-and-a-history-of-the-neighboring-communities/|title=Underutilized Tracks: A Chronicle of Electric Train Service to East Williston and a History of the Neighboring Communities|last=Stadler|first=Derek|date=November 15, 2014|website=Derek Stadler|access-date=May 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===20th century to present===\nThe line was double-tracked to Roslyn, Glen Cove and Locust Valley in 1905, 1909 and 1911, respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112089483272;view=1up;seq=80|title=The Long Island Railroad Twenty-Seventh Annual Report For The Year Ending December 31st, 1908|last=|first=|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=1909|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|19}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ijgwAQAAMAAJ&dq=oyster+bay+branch+second+track+1911&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=locust+valley|title=Annual Report of the Long Island Rail Road Company to the Interstate Commerce Commission for the Year Ended December 31, 1911|last=|first=|date=1912|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 24, 1911|title=New Incorporations, Surveys, Etc.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SwQjAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA368&dq=glen+cove+chamber+of+commerce+oyster+bay+branch+electrification&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ2bO31fHaAhUCMt8KHXoGC78Q6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=glen%20cove%20chamber%20of%20commerce%20oyster%20bay%20branch%20electrification&f=false|journal=Railway Age|volume=50|issue=8|pages=368|via=}}</ref> The extension of the line's second track was done in anticipation of electrification.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112089483272;view=1up;seq=80|title=The Long Island Railroad Twenty-Eighth Annual Report For The Year Ending December 31st, 1909|last=|first=|publisher=Long Island Railroad Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|21}}\n\nUntil 1928, a direct connection to the [[West Hempstead Branch]] existed just east of Mineola station. This spur crossed the [[Main Line (Long Island Rail Road)|Main Line]], then terminated at the end of a wye at what was often called the Garden City Branch. Until passenger service was abandoned along this branch, passengers would transfer between the two lines at Mineola Station itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lirrhistory.com/minwhemp.html|title=Mineola to West Hempstead|work=lirrhistory.com}}</ref><ref>[http://trainsarefun.com/lirr/mineola/mineola.htm Mineola Station History (Steve Lynch's LIRR Maps, Photos, Charts, etc.)] (TrainsAreFun.com)</ref> \n\nIn November 1928, LIRR officials surveyed the branch to evaluate the feasibility of electrifying the line. The Glen Cove Chamber of Commerce petitioned the LIRR, advocating for electrification. In response, the Vice President of the LIRR, in December, stated that the LIRR had to deal with the completion of multiple grade crossing elimination projects before electrifying the Oyster Bay Branch, which was estimated to cost $3.28 million.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 15, 1928|title=Position of L.I. On Oyster Bay Electrification|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lZYlAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1203&dq=oyster+bay+branch+electrification&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlsLL0PHaAhWhxFkKHa7SAs0Q6AEIPDAD#v=onepage&q=oyster%20bay%20branch%20electrification&f=false|journal=Railway Age|publisher=Simmons\u2013Boardman Publishing Company|volume=85|issue=24|pages=1203|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBy June 1934, the section of the line between [[East Williston (LIRR station)|East Williston]] and [[Mineola (LIRR station)|Mineola]] was electrified, with the remainder of the branch expected to be electrified soon after.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|40}} However, the remainder of the work was not completed. Instead, the branch is served by diesel powered-locomotive trains (except for one AM peak train that originates at East Williston and ends at [[Pennsylvania Station (New York)|Penn Station]] using Electric-Multiple Units).<ref name=\"LIRR Stations\">{{cite book |last=Morrison |first=David D. |last2=Pakaluk |first2=Valerie |title=Long Island Rail Road Stations |year=2003 |publisher=Arcadia |location=Chicago |isbn=0-7385-1180-3 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=20BUDIVc-5AC&pg=PA57 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the LIRR replaced the bridge over West Shore Road between Locust Valley and Oyster Bay Stations.<ref>[http://web.mta.info/lirr/News/2009/OysterBay11-2009a.htm Vans Replace Oyster Bay Trains Weekend of November 21-22 (MTA-LIRR News; November 2009)]</ref>\n\n==Stations==\nWest of {{lirrs|Mineola}}, most trips go on to terminate at {{lirrs|Jamaica}}, with some rush hour trips ending at {{lirrs|Hunterspoint Avenue}} or {{lirrs|Penn Station}}.<ref name=timetable>[http://mta.info/lirr/Timetable/Branch/OysterBayBranch.pdf LIRR Oyster Bay Branch Timetable]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Zone\n!Location\n!Station\n![[Railway milepost|Miles (km)]]<br>from [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|NYP]]<ref>Station pages linked from [http://lirr42.mta.info/stations LIRR Stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907052709/http://lirr42.mta.info/stations |date=September 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n!Date<br>opened\n!Date<br>closed\n!Connections and notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|4\n|[[Mineola, New York|Mineola]]\n|{{lirrs|Mineola}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|20.3 (32.3)\n|1837\n|\n|[[Long Island Rail Road]]: [[Montauk Branch|Montauk]], [[Port Jefferson Branch|Port Jefferson]], [[Ronkonkoma Branch|Ronkonkoma]] branches<br>[[Nassau Inter-County Express]]: {{LI bus link|n22|n22X|N23|n24|n40|n41}}<br>Originally named Hempstead, then Branch or Hempstead Branch\n|-\n|[[East Williston, New York|East Williston]]\n|{{lirrs|East Williston}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|21.6 (34.8)\n|1880<ref name=\"East Williston\">{{cite book |last=Morrison |first=David D. |last2=Pakaluk |first2=Valerie |title=Long Island Rail Road Stations |year=2003 |publisher=Arcadia |location=Chicago |isbn=0-7385-1180-3 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=20BUDIVc-5AC&pg=PA57 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}<br>Terminus of [[railway electrification system|electrification]]\n|-\n|rowspan=11|7\n|[[Albertson, New York|Albertson]]\n|{{lirrs|Albertson}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|22.6 (36.4)\n|1875\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}\n|-\n|[[Roslyn, New York|Roslyn]]\n|{{lirrs|Roslyn}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|24.0 (38.6)\n|January 23, 1865\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n23|n27}}\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n|[[Wheatley Hills, New York|Wheatley Hills]]\n|{{lirrs|North Roslyn}}\n|\n|\n|1924\n|Originally named Wheatley Hills\n|-\n|[[Greenvale, New York|Greenvale]]\n|{{lirrs|Greenvale}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|26.0 (41.8)\n|1866\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}<br>Originally named Week's\n|-\n|[[Glen Head, New York|Glen Head]]\n|{{lirrs|Glen Head}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|27.2 (43.8)\n|January 23, 1865\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Glen Cove, New York|Glen Cove]]\n|{{lirrs|Sea Cliff}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|28.5 (45.9)\n|May 16, 1867\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n27}}\n|-\n|{{lirrs|Glen Street}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|29.1 (45.2)\n|May 16, 1867\n|\n|Nassau Inter-County Express: {{LI bus link|n21|n27}}\n|-\n|{{lirrs|Glen Cove}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|29.7 (47.8)\n|1895\n|\n|Originally named Nassau\n|-\n|[[Locust Valley, New York|Locust Valley]]\n|{{lirrs|Locust Valley}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|30.8 (49.6)\n|April 19, 1869\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=dfdfdf\n|[[Mill Neck, New York|Mill Neck]]\n|{{lirrs|Mill Neck}}\n|\n|June 25, 1889\n|1998\n|Originally named Bayville\n|-\n|[[Oyster Bay, New York|Oyster Bay]]\n|{{lirrs|Oyster Bay}} {{LIRR acc}}\n|34.7 (55.8)\n|June 25, 1889\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons and category|Oyster Bay Branch|Oyster Bay Branch (Long Island Rail Road)}}\n* [http://www.lirrhistory.com/obsta.html Oyster Bay Branch Stations (Unofficial LIRR History web site)]\n* [http://world.nycsubway.org/us/lirr/lirr-oysterbay.html NYCSubways.org: Oyster Bay Branch]\n* [http://thelirrtoday.blogspot.com/search/label/Oyster%20Bay%20Branch Oyster Bay Branch (The LIRR Today)]\n\n{{Long Island Rail Road}}\n\n[[Category:Long Island Rail Road branches]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Nassau County, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "add short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oyster_Bay_Branch"}
{"title_page": "Charles H. Clausen", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Charles H. Clausen\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1842|09|22}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1922|08|15|1842|09|22}}\n|birth_place   = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|death_place   = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|placeofburial = [[Mount Peace Cemetery]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|allegiance    = [[United States of America]]\n|branch        = [[United States Army]]<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears  = 1861 - 1865\n|rank          = [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n|unit          = {{flagicon|Pennsylvania}} [[61st Pennsylvania Infantry Regiment|61st Regiment, Pennsylvania Volunteer Infantry]] - Company H\n|battles       = [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''Charles H. Clausen''' (September 22, 1842 - August 15, 1922) was an American soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Clausen received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]] in [[Virginia]] on 12 May 1864. He was honored with the award on 25 June 1892.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Projects\">{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=411 |title=Charles H. Clausen |accessdate=27 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203243/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=411# |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"CMOHS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/261/clausen-charles-h.php |title=Clausen, Charles H. |accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nClausen was born in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] on 22 September 1842. He enlisted into the 17th Pennsylvania Infantry. While in this unit he was involved in battles at Washington, D.C. and along the [[Potomac River|Potomac]] in Virginia. After the expiration of the three-month service in the 17th Infantry he mustered into [[61st Pennsylvania Infantry]] on 21 August 1861 as first sergeant. He was later promoted to first sergeant. While serving in this capacity he was involved in the [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]] in Virginia. It was during this battle that he performed the act of gallantry that earned him the Medal of Honor. He was wounded during this battle but returned to his battalion as [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] and then commander in October 1864. On 10 February 1865 he eventually resigned from active service due to his injuries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://antietam.aotw.org/officers.php?officer_id=1039 |title=Charles H Clausen |accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nClausen died on 15 August 1922 and his remains are interred at the [[Mount Peace Cemetery]] in Philadelphia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charles H. Clausen |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/5541/charles-h_-clausen |website=www.findagrave.com |accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Although severely wounded, he led the regiment against the enemy, under a terrific fire, and saved a battery from capture.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"Projects\"/><ref name=\"CMOHS\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clausen, Charles H.}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Pennsylvania in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Peace Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Charles H. Clausen\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1842|09|22}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1922|08|15|1842|09|22}}\n|birth_place   = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|death_place   = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|placeofburial = [[Mount Peace Cemetery]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|allegiance    = [[United States of America]]\n|branch        = [[United States Army]]<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears  = 1861 - 1865\n|rank          = [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n|unit          = Company H, [[61st Pennsylvania Infantry]]\n|battles       = [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''Charles H. Clausen''' (September 22, 1842 - August 15, 1922) was an American soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Clausen received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]] in [[Virginia]] on 12 May 1864. He was honored with the award on 25 June 1892.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Projects\">{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=411 |title=Charles H. Clausen |accessdate=27 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203243/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=411# |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"CMOHS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/261/clausen-charles-h.php |title=Clausen, Charles H. |accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nClausen was born in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] on 22 September 1842. He enlisted into the 17th Pennsylvania Infantry. While in this unit he was involved in battles at Washington, D.C. and along the [[Potomac River|Potomac]] in Virginia. After the expiration of the three-month service in the 17th Infantry he mustered into [[61st Pennsylvania Infantry]] on 21 August 1861 as first sergeant. He was later promoted to first sergeant. While serving in this capacity he was involved in the [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]] in Virginia. It was during this battle that he performed the act of gallantry that earned him the Medal of Honor. He was wounded during this battle but returned to his battalion as [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] and then commander in October 1864. On 10 February 1865 he eventually resigned from active service due to his injuries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://antietam.aotw.org/officers.php?officer_id=1039 |title=Charles H Clausen |accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nClausen died on 15 August 1922 and his remains are interred at the [[Mount Peace Cemetery]] in Philadelphia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charles H. Clausen |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/5541/charles-h_-clausen |website=www.findagrave.com |accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Although severely wounded, he led the regiment against the enemy, under a terrific fire, and saved a battery from capture.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"Projects\"/><ref name=\"CMOHS\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clausen, Charles H.}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Pennsylvania in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Peace Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_H._Clausen"}
{"title_page": "Annalisa Piras", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:Piras pic.jpg|thumb|Annalisa Piras]]\n\n'''Annalisa Piras ''' is a London-based Italian film director, producer and journalist. She is currently the director of Springshot Productions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://springshotproductions.com|title=Springshot Production website}}</ref> an independent production company which specialises in documentaries. She also directs The Wake Up Foundation, an educational charity she co-founded with Bill Emmott,former editor of The Economist. In 2019 The Wake Up Foundation founded and run the first Wake Up Europe Impact Films Festival,the first ever transnational impact documentary festival entirely devoted to showcase the best films produced worldwide to highlights the shared challenges our western societies face, with a special focus on the meaning of a European civic conscience. The Wake Up Europe Festival offered a \"selection for reflection\" of 10 films, which were screened and debated in Turin,Italy and across other nine European locations <ref>{{citen web|url=https://www.torinoggi.it/2019/05/18/leggi-notizia/argomenti/eventi-11/articolo/domani-chiude-a-torino-wake-up-europe-festival.html}}</ref>\n\nPiras'2016 film, \"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte]] and [[SVT]] was nominated for the 2016 Prix Europa, the Oscar of European Documentaries. It was broadcast across the world in 2017. The film looks at Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's transnational security challenges and the shifting sands of geopolitics.It gained exclusive access for the first time to the EU top diplomat, the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policies Federica Mogherini. \n\nIn 2015 Annalisa Piras directed \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d, the first ever film on the EU crisis from an international point of view.<ref>''[http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about \"The Great European Disaster Movie - About\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529160739/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about |date=2015-05-29 }}'', thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu, May 29, 2015</ref> It was produced by [[BBC]] and [[Arte]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4288614/|title=IMDB The Great European Disaster Movie}}</ref>\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film was selected among 930 applications from media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in May 2016.\n\n==Career==\n\nAs EU senior editor, Piras was part of the initial team which launched [[Euronews]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3ci3eNe6Dc|title=Youtube-Annalisa Piras-Euronews}}</ref> the pan-European multilingual news television channel, on 1 January 1993 in Lyon, France.\n\nPiras was the London Correspondent for ''[[L'Espresso]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/chi-sono/|title=Annalisa Piras-L'Espresso-chi sono}}</ref>'' from 1997 to 2011 and for La7 TV{{cn|date=January 2020}} for six years. From 2006 to 2007 Annalisa was the first Italian president of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120315000217/http://www.fpalondon.org/showarticle.pl?id=43%3Bn=142%20 London Foreign Press Association].\n\nIn 2008, Piras' BBC Radio 4 documentary [http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml ''The Italian Patient'']<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w0006q6d|title=The Documentary-The Italian Patient}}</ref> was shortlisted as the FPA Best Story of the Year by a UK-based foreign correspondent.  Her TV documentary on the [[Hutton Enquiry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/tag/hutton-inquiry/|title=L'Espresso-Hutton Enquiry}}</ref> written and directed for La7 TV, was shortlisted for the same award in 2003.\n\nIn 2011 and 2012 Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy seen from abroad, [[Girlfriend in a Coma (film)|Girlfriend in a Coma]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> co-written and narrated by [[Bill Emmott]], former editor of ''The Economist'', inspired by his book ''Good Italy, Bad Italy'' (Yale University Press).\n\nPiras collected the 2011 PEN/Pinter prize on behalf of Italian writer, [[Roberto Saviano]], who was unable to attend the ceremony in person because of the failure of the metropolitan police to offer him adequate protection. In addressing Saviano's life under the shadow of Mafia death threats, Piras delivered a speech in honour of his courage, \"with a passion that was raw, exposed and moving\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/oct/14/slovo-pen-prize-roberto-saviano|title=The Guardian: Gillian Slovo: the courage of Roberto Saviano}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Piras founded the Wake Up Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wakeupfoundation.eu|title=The Wake Up Foundation website}}</ref> with the aim to raise public awareness about the current state and decline of the Western Societies through film and storytelling. Through the Wake Up Foundation, Piras and Bill Emmott launched in 2013 the campaign Wake Up Europe! to foster political debate and citizen's participation about the greatest challenges facing Europe. The Wake Up Europe Campaign has since been organising hundreds of documentary screenings and debates across the world, from the Italian Parliament, Montecitorio to a small Town Hall in Denmark or prestigious Universities such as Oxford or Cambridge, the campaign has engaged thousands of citizens fostering informed debates about the future of our societies. \n\nIn 2014 Piras wrote, directed and produced with Bill Emmott the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]] co-produced by Nick Fraser for the BBC Storyville strand, Claudia Bucher, for Arte TV, Axel Arno for SVT, Swedish public Tv.\n\n\"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte|ARTE]] and [[SVT]] and written, produced and directed by Piras followed for two years the footsteps of [[Federica Mogherini]], the High Representative of the European Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy, as she tried to implement the EU Global Strategy, while facing a relentless series of crisis, andunexpected turns, from the vote on Brexit, to the election of President Trump, to the deepening of the refugees and migrants challenge in the South Mediterranean. The film is an unique document to analyses Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's challenges from the perspective of the person called upon to implement a shared European vision, which is sorely elusive.\n\nPiras is a regular member of the BBC ''[[Dateline London]]'' panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isthebbcbiased.blogspot.co.uk/2012/11/dateline-guest-of-dishonour.html|title=Dateline Guests}}</ref>\nShe also provided [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa analysis] on European and Italian Current Affairs for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa}}</ref>\n\nAs a political and social commentator she frequently appears on BBC News, Sky News, CNN, Al Jazeera and CNBC.\n\n== Girlfriend in a Coma ==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn 2012 Annalisa Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy as seen from abroad, Girlfriend in a Coma,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> working with Bill Emmott, former editor of The Economist, as co-author and narrator.<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2315588/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_2 \"Girlfriend in a Coma\"]'', IMDb, imdb.com, May 29, 2015</ref> The film was made by Springshot Productions.\n\nThe documentary is inspired by Emmott\u2019s book Good Italy, Bad Italy (Yale University Press), as well as by Piras\u2019s patriotic passion and insight about the country she left in the early 1990s.\nThe film aims to introduce Italians and the World to the dark side of the country's political, economic and social decline, the product of a moral collapse in the West. It was broadcast on BBC Four, Sky Italia and La7 TV channels early in 2013, and subsequently on other channels worldwide as well as in public screenings.\n\nThe \u201cGirlfriend in a Coma\u201d title is a citation of a British musical hit by The Smiths from their album Strangeways (1987).\n\n== The Great European Disaster Movie ==\n\nIn 2014 Annalisa Piras wrote, directed and produced with [[Bill Emmott]] the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]]. In an artfully constructed depiction of how Europe is sleepwalking toward disaster, starring Angus Deayton in fiction scenes from a postEU future, the film pairs an imagined view from a dystopian future with insightful, cross national analysis by ordinary Europeans and high level experts on how and why things are going so wrong. Notable interviewees include French economist [[Thomas Piketty]], [[Martin Wolf]], chief economic commentator at the Financial Times, former EU trade commissioner [[Peter Mandelson]], and many former ministers and high level EU officials in various European countries.\n\nIn an authored piece of committed journalism, the filmmakers argue powerfully that, while economic crisis and popular anger are pushing Europe dangerously towards disintegration, the EU is in need of major reform but well worth saving. Subtle, moving, thoughtprovoking and witty, \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d is far more than a political film but instead frames Europe through the eyes of those who are most important to its success: the Europeans themselves.\n\n'''Reception'''\n\nThe Great European Disaster Movie is a BBC/ARTE and 7 other European broadcasters coproduction, which has now been watched by 2.360.000 viewers, one million of which in France and Germany. The film premi\u00e8red on BBC Four, as part of the Storyville strand, on 1 March 2015. It was subsequently broadcast in 12 countries (UK, France, Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Belgium, Italy, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway and Japan) and has been translated in 10 languages, including Japanese.\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d has won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film has been selected among 930 applications by media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in the presence of EU broadcasters yesterday evening May 12.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160514121408/http://www.dw.com/en/civis-media-awards-presented-in-berlin/av-19255971 Watch the video]\n \n'''Controversy'''\n\nThe film generated a great deal of media controversy in the UK, with some critics taking exception at the BBC broadcasting an authored piece with an overtly pro-European slant and others accusing the authors of scaremongering. The BBC broadcast was followed by a live studio debate on Newsnight, the BBC\u2019s news and current affairs programme, during which exec producer Bill Emmott faced several prominent eurosceptic critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|title=The Great European Disaster Movie was meant to stimulate robust debate on Europe's future. What we got was a theological war|work=britishinfluence.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928224214/http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|archivedate=2015-09-28}}</ref>\n\nDirector Annalisa Piras responded to the attacks in a piece for the Guardian and refuted the points more fully on the film\u2019s website in a joint piece with Emmott.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html |title=Nine things The Great European Disaster Movie got wrong |work=telegraph.co.uk/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |title=Nine Things that Toby Young Got Wrong |work=thegreateuropeandiastermovie.eu/ |access-date=2015-09-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929001311/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |archive-date=2015-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBoth Piras and Emmott became the subjects of vitriolic attacks on Twitter by people who argued the film was a piece of \u2018EU propaganda\u2019 despite its strong criticism of the EU institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/05/britain-debate-europe-the-great-european-disaster-movie |title=Is Britain even capable of constructive debate on Europe?|work=theguardian.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n\n\n'''Other Reactions'''\n\nIn his review for The Independent [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/we-could-find-ourselves-back-in-the-europe-of-our-nightmares-10012154.html We could find ourselves back into the Europe of our nightmares.], John Popham called film is a \u201cwake-up call for all those for whom departure from the union could not come a moment too soon and would be the one-stop solution to all our ills, from immigration to health-and-safety nannying\u201d.  The film also received positive coverage in Italy where it was reviewed by [[Il Sole 24]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/commenti-e-idee/2015-04-18/l-europa-filo-disastro-091043_PRN.shtml|title=L'Europa sul filo del disastro|work=ilsole24ore.com/}}</ref> [[Il Fatto Quotidiano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2015/02/15/the-great-european-disaster-movie-la-fidanzata-in-coma-ora-e-leuropa/1426845/  |title=la 'fidanzata in coma' ora \u00e8 l'Europa}}</ref> and [[La Repubblica]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2015/04/17/cera-una-volta-leuropa-unita-la-crisi-in-un-film36.html |title=C'era una volta l'Europa unita la crisi in un film|work=ricerca.repubblica.it/}}</ref> and France. In his review for La Stampa, Brussels Correspondent Marco Zatterin argued that the film unleashed such a \u201cviolent\u201d reaction among British eurosceptics because it \u201cinvaded their territory by criticising Europe but with a view to rebuild it.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2015/03/07/blogs/straneuropa/un-film-contro-il-monopolio-euroscettico-odijJnPxeMkB3lsdxzanUO/pagina.html |title=Un film contro il monopolio euroscettico|work=lastampa.it/}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SU5RCvHSzTM/Backstage Video of \"Girlfriend In a Coma\" Screening at ICA - London]\n* [http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/cultura/2012-12-09/Il riscatto-amica-coma-081838.shtml?uuid=AbgfySAH/ Il riscatto dell'amica in coma. Il Sole 24 Ore]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa/]\n* [http://www.lastampa.it/2012/12/10/societa/l-italia-una-fidanzata-in-coma-XBtP2LdLucrnfW6RevWAxM/pagina.html \"Chi sveglier\u00e0 la ragazza in coma?\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121113073111/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090521012855/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8044711.stm]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090214234701/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7583739.stm]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HTCuI2d12jQ]\n* [http://wakeupfoundation.eu/ The Wake Up Foundation]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piras, Annalisa}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian journalists]]\n[[Category:Italian film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:Piras pic.jpg|thumb|Annalisa Piras]]\n\n'''Annalisa Piras ''' is a London-based Italian film director, producer and journalist. She is currently the director of Springshot Productions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://springshotproductions.com|title=Springshot Production website}}</ref> an independent production company which specialises in documentaries. She also directs The Wake Up Foundation, an educational charity she co-founded with Bill Emmott,former editor of The Economist. \n\nPiras'2016 film, \"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte]] and [[SVT]] was nominated for the 2016 Prix Europa, the Oscar of European Documentaries. It was broadcast across the world in 2017. The film looks at Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's transnational security challenges and the shifting sands of geopolitics.It gained exclusive access for the first time to the EU top diplomat, the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policies Federica Mogherini. \n\nIn 2015 Annalisa Piras directed \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d, the first ever film on the EU crisis from an international point of view.<ref>''[http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about \"The Great European Disaster Movie - About\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529160739/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/about |date=2015-05-29 }}'', thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu, May 29, 2015</ref> It was produced by [[BBC]] and [[Arte]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4288614/|title=IMDB The Great European Disaster Movie}}</ref>\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film was selected among 930 applications from media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in May 2016.\n\n==Career==\n\nAs EU senior editor, Piras was part of the initial team which launched [[Euronews]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3ci3eNe6Dc|title=Youtube-Annalisa Piras-Euronews}}</ref> the pan-European multilingual news television channel, on 1 January 1993 in Lyon, France.\n\nPiras was the London Correspondent for ''[[L'Espresso]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/chi-sono/|title=Annalisa Piras-L'Espresso-chi sono}}</ref>'' from 1997 to 2011 and for La7 TV{{cn|date=January 2020}} for six years. From 2006 to 2007 Annalisa was the first Italian president of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120315000217/http://www.fpalondon.org/showarticle.pl?id=43%3Bn=142%20 London Foreign Press Association].\n\nIn 2008, Piras' BBC Radio 4 documentary [http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml ''The Italian Patient'']<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w0006q6d|title=The Documentary-The Italian Patient}}</ref> was shortlisted as the FPA Best Story of the Year by a UK-based foreign correspondent.  Her TV documentary on the [[Hutton Enquiry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piras.blogautore.espresso.repubblica.it/tag/hutton-inquiry/|title=L'Espresso-Hutton Enquiry}}</ref> written and directed for La7 TV, was shortlisted for the same award in 2003.\n\nIn 2011 and 2012 Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy seen from abroad, [[Girlfriend in a Coma (film)|Girlfriend in a Coma]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> co-written and narrated by [[Bill Emmott]], former editor of ''The Economist'', inspired by his book ''Good Italy, Bad Italy'' (Yale University Press).\n\nPiras collected the 2011 PEN/Pinter prize on behalf of Italian writer, [[Roberto Saviano]], who was unable to attend the ceremony in person because of the failure of the metropolitan police to offer him adequate protection. In addressing Saviano's life under the shadow of Mafia death threats, Piras delivered a speech in honour of his courage, \"with a passion that was raw, exposed and moving\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/oct/14/slovo-pen-prize-roberto-saviano|title=The Guardian: Gillian Slovo: the courage of Roberto Saviano}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Piras founded the Wake Up Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wakeupfoundation.eu|title=The Wake Up Foundation website}}</ref> with the aim to raise public awareness about the current state and decline of the Western Societies through film and storytelling. Through the Wake Up Foundation, Piras and Bill Emmott launched in 2013 the campaign Wake Up Europe! to foster political debate and citizen's participation about the greatest challenges facing Europe. The Wake Up Europe Campaign has since been organising hundreds of documentary screenings and debates across the world, from the Italian Parliament, Montecitorio to a small Town Hall in Denmark or prestigious Universities such as Oxford or Cambridge, the campaign has engaged thousands of citizens fostering informed debates about the future of our societies. \n\nIn 2014 Piras wrote, directed and produced with Bill Emmott the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]] co-produced by Nick Fraser for the BBC Storyville strand, Claudia Bucher, for Arte TV, Axel Arno for SVT, Swedish public Tv.\n\n\"Europe at Sea\", a feature-length documentary co-produced by [[Arte|ARTE]] and [[SVT]] and written, produced and directed by Piras followed for two years the footsteps of [[Federica Mogherini]], the High Representative of the European Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy, as she tried to implement the EU Global Strategy, while facing a relentless series of crisis, andunexpected turns, from the vote on Brexit, to the election of President Trump, to the deepening of the refugees and migrants challenge in the South Mediterranean. The film is an unique document to analyses Europe's role on the global stage in light of today's challenges from the perspective of the person called upon to implement a shared European vision, which is sorely elusive.\n\nPiras is a regular member of the BBC ''[[Dateline London]]'' panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isthebbcbiased.blogspot.co.uk/2012/11/dateline-guest-of-dishonour.html|title=Dateline Guests}}</ref>\nShe also provided [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa analysis] on European and Italian Current Affairs for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa}}</ref>\n\nAs a political and social commentator she frequently appears on BBC News, Sky News, CNN, Al Jazeera and CNBC.\n\n== Girlfriend in a Coma ==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn 2012 Annalisa Piras produced, co-wrote and directed the first independent feature documentary on Italy as seen from abroad, Girlfriend in a Coma,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girlfriendinacoma.eu|title=Girlfriend In A Coma website}}</ref> working with Bill Emmott, former editor of The Economist, as co-author and narrator.<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2315588/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_2 \"Girlfriend in a Coma\"]'', IMDb, imdb.com, May 29, 2015</ref> The film was made by Springshot Productions.\n\nThe documentary is inspired by Emmott\u2019s book Good Italy, Bad Italy (Yale University Press), as well as by Piras\u2019s patriotic passion and insight about the country she left in the early 1990s.\nThe film aims to introduce Italians and the World to the dark side of the country's political, economic and social decline, the product of a moral collapse in the West. It was broadcast on BBC Four, Sky Italia and La7 TV channels early in 2013, and subsequently on other channels worldwide as well as in public screenings.\n\nThe \u201cGirlfriend in a Coma\u201d title is a citation of a British musical hit by The Smiths from their album Strangeways (1987).\n\n== The Great European Disaster Movie ==\n\nIn 2014 Annalisa Piras wrote, directed and produced with [[Bill Emmott]] the documentary  \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d on the crisis of the [[European Union]]. In an artfully constructed depiction of how Europe is sleepwalking toward disaster, starring Angus Deayton in fiction scenes from a postEU future, the film pairs an imagined view from a dystopian future with insightful, cross national analysis by ordinary Europeans and high level experts on how and why things are going so wrong. Notable interviewees include French economist [[Thomas Piketty]], [[Martin Wolf]], chief economic commentator at the Financial Times, former EU trade commissioner [[Peter Mandelson]], and many former ministers and high level EU officials in various European countries.\n\nIn an authored piece of committed journalism, the filmmakers argue powerfully that, while economic crisis and popular anger are pushing Europe dangerously towards disintegration, the EU is in need of major reform but well worth saving. Subtle, moving, thoughtprovoking and witty, \u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d is far more than a political film but instead frames Europe through the eyes of those who are most important to its success: the Europeans themselves.\n\n'''Reception'''\n\nThe Great European Disaster Movie is a BBC/ARTE and 7 other European broadcasters coproduction, which has now been watched by 2.360.000 viewers, one million of which in France and Germany. The film premi\u00e8red on BBC Four, as part of the Storyville strand, on 1 March 2015. It was subsequently broadcast in 12 countries (UK, France, Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Belgium, Italy, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway and Japan) and has been translated in 10 languages, including Japanese.\n\n\u201cThe Great European Disaster Movie\u201d has won the prestigious German CIVIS media prize in the information category. The film has been selected among 930 applications by media programmes from all over Europe. The prize was bestowed by the German Federal President Joachim Gauck and the President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz at a star studded event in the German Federal Foreign Office in Berlin in the presence of EU broadcasters yesterday evening May 12.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160514121408/http://www.dw.com/en/civis-media-awards-presented-in-berlin/av-19255971 Watch the video]\n \n'''Controversy'''\n\nThe film generated a great deal of media controversy in the UK, with some critics taking exception at the BBC broadcasting an authored piece with an overtly pro-European slant and others accusing the authors of scaremongering. The BBC broadcast was followed by a live studio debate on Newsnight, the BBC\u2019s news and current affairs programme, during which exec producer Bill Emmott faced several prominent eurosceptic critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|title=The Great European Disaster Movie was meant to stimulate robust debate on Europe's future. What we got was a theological war|work=britishinfluence.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928224214/http://www.britishinfluence.org/the_great_european_disaster_movie_was_meant_to_stimulate_robust_debate_on_europe_s_future_what_we_got_was_a_theological_war|archivedate=2015-09-28}}</ref>\n\nDirector Annalisa Piras responded to the attacks in a piece for the Guardian and refuted the points more fully on the film\u2019s website in a joint piece with Emmott.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html |title=Nine things The Great European Disaster Movie got wrong |work=telegraph.co.uk/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |title=Nine Things that Toby Young Got Wrong |work=thegreateuropeandiastermovie.eu/ |access-date=2015-09-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929001311/http://www.thegreateuropeandisastermovie.eu/nine_things_that_toby_young_got_wrong |archive-date=2015-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBoth Piras and Emmott became the subjects of vitriolic attacks on Twitter by people who argued the film was a piece of \u2018EU propaganda\u2019 despite its strong criticism of the EU institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/05/britain-debate-europe-the-great-european-disaster-movie |title=Is Britain even capable of constructive debate on Europe?|work=theguardian.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n\n\n'''Other Reactions'''\n\nIn his review for The Independent [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/we-could-find-ourselves-back-in-the-europe-of-our-nightmares-10012154.html We could find ourselves back into the Europe of our nightmares.], John Popham called film is a \u201cwake-up call for all those for whom departure from the union could not come a moment too soon and would be the one-stop solution to all our ills, from immigration to health-and-safety nannying\u201d.  The film also received positive coverage in Italy where it was reviewed by [[Il Sole 24]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/commenti-e-idee/2015-04-18/l-europa-filo-disastro-091043_PRN.shtml|title=L'Europa sul filo del disastro|work=ilsole24ore.com/}}</ref> [[Il Fatto Quotidiano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2015/02/15/the-great-european-disaster-movie-la-fidanzata-in-coma-ora-e-leuropa/1426845/  |title=la 'fidanzata in coma' ora \u00e8 l'Europa}}</ref> and [[La Repubblica]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2015/04/17/cera-una-volta-leuropa-unita-la-crisi-in-un-film36.html |title=C'era una volta l'Europa unita la crisi in un film|work=ricerca.repubblica.it/}}</ref> and France. In his review for La Stampa, Brussels Correspondent Marco Zatterin argued that the film unleashed such a \u201cviolent\u201d reaction among British eurosceptics because it \u201cinvaded their territory by criticising Europe but with a view to rebuild it.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2015/03/07/blogs/straneuropa/un-film-contro-il-monopolio-euroscettico-odijJnPxeMkB3lsdxzanUO/pagina.html |title=Un film contro il monopolio euroscettico|work=lastampa.it/}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SU5RCvHSzTM/Backstage Video of \"Girlfriend In a Coma\" Screening at ICA - London]\n* [http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/cultura/2012-12-09/Il riscatto-amica-coma-081838.shtml?uuid=AbgfySAH/ Il riscatto dell'amica in coma. Il Sole 24 Ore]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/piras-annalisa/]\n* [http://www.lastampa.it/2012/12/10/societa/l-italia-una-fidanzata-in-coma-XBtP2LdLucrnfW6RevWAxM/pagina.html \"Chi sveglier\u00e0 la ragazza in coma?\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121113073111/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/documentaries/2008/10/081007_italian_patient.shtml]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090521012855/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8044711.stm]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090214234701/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7583739.stm]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HTCuI2d12jQ]\n* [http://wakeupfoundation.eu/ The Wake Up Foundation]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11445299/The-Great-European-Disaster-Movie-10-things-it-got-wrong.html]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piras, Annalisa}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian journalists]]\n[[Category:Italian film directors]]\n", "name_user": "Urban-stories", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annalisa_Piras"}
{"title_page": "Rural Municipality of Blucher No. 343", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = RM of Blucher\n| official_name                   = Rural Municipality of Blucher No. 343\n| settlement_type                 = Rural Municipality\n| pushpin_map                     = Saskatchewan\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|52|00|43|N|106|10|06|W}}\n| subdivision_type                = Canada\n| subdivision_name                = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type1               = Province\n| subdivision_name1               = Saskatchewan\n| established_title               = Establishment\n| established_date                = 1909\n| leader_title                    = Reeve\n| leader_name                     = Dan Greschuk\n|leader_title1 = Office Location\n|leader_name1 = [[Bradwell, Saskatchewan|Bradwell]]\n| area_land_km2                   = 789.64\n| population_total                = 2,006\n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_density_km2          = 2.5\n| area_code                       = 306\n| website                         = https://www.rm343.com/\n| leader_title1                   = Office Location\n}}\n\n'''Blucher No. 343''' is a [[rural municipality]] in north-central [[Saskatchewan]] on the [[South Saskatchewan River]]. The municipality office is located in the village of [[Bradwell, Saskatchewan|Bradwell]]. It is located in [[Division No. 11, Saskatchewan|Division No. 11]]. In 1958, the Patience Lake mine was the first potash mine built in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rm343.com/wp442/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/RM-of-Blucher-Official-Community-Plan.pdf|title=RM of Blucher Official Community Plan|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=2017-06-19}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Canada census|2016_access_date=2017-06-08|2016_land_area=789.64|2016_mean_hh_income=|2016_median_age=40.2|2016_median_age_f=39.5|2016_median_age_m=40.8|2016_pop_delta=6.9|2016_pop_density=2.5|2016_population=2,006|2016_tota